					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/scroton" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1388358); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1388358&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610205819" alt="scroton" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1388358)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/scroton" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1388358); return false;" >scroton</a></span> <span class="odate time_1342693816 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 Jul 2012 10:30</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1512080">
									

<p>I know I'm replying to comments from years ago, but the reason lobotomies are no longer performed is largely because of the advent of Thorazine, which produces calming and mental dampening effects similar to those brought about via lobotomy while being much more consistent in their effect (not every lobotomy worked as intended), completely reversible and not carrying any of the surgery-related complications that lobotomies could bring. At the time when they were first introduced lobotomies were a godsend because it meant that a lot of people that would otherwise have remained in sanitoriums for the rest of their lives were able to return to at least semi-normal lives, even if they weren't quite all there.</p>
<p>I'm assuming the reason it's used here is because the desired effect isn't the calming/mental dampening effect of a lobotomy but rather the &quot;prevent the frontal lobe from continuing to function&quot; part of it. Lobotomies do have the advantage of being very quickly and easily applied compared to surgery, which may be desirable in the case of this SCP.</p>

							</div>

								
					
