														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-859746">
									

<p>Actually, I believe he's referring to Walter Jackson Freeman II, a member of the APA, and one of the guys that really helped lobotomies get established as a medical practice. During his career, he did over 2500 of them… No, that's not a typo.. twenty five HUNDRED of them.. *Edited from my typo'd ver that said 25k*</p>
<p>And, yeah. They are a very questionable procedure… Freeman didn't want to even do it the standard surgical way, drilling holes and using a wire loop… Too hard, expensive, and required a proper surgical room and staff. So he experimented with corpses and a icepick from his kitchen, and came up with a method that involved pounding a hold in upper eye socket, then wiggling the icepick around to cause damage to the frontal lobe. High precision surgery, clearly.</p>
<p>The advent of better drugs drove out the need for such ham-handed foolishness, and they eventually revoked his license to practice medicine.</p>
<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walter_Freeman_%28surgeon%29">If you want to read up on him, here's the Wiki link</a></p>
<p>I like the idea of it referring to Gordon Freeman, too.. But I'm pretty sure he meant the icepick-wielding butcher.</p>

